<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="656" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="37.[2073,2667,2641,3069]" lastBlockId="37.[1460,2665,3075,3462]" pageId="37" pageNumber="656">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2073,2323,2918,2951]" pageId="37" pageNumber="656">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 81-90 mm, tall 34-44 mm, ear 18-25 mm, hindfoot 11-15 mm, forearm 51-55 mm. Fur is short, sleek and almost lacking across shoulder, medium sepia-brown or yellowish brown with no grizzling spots above, with dark patch behind and below ear; below pale grayish brown, pale pinkish gray or pale yellowish brown becoming darker on flanks, with no mid-ventral markings or contrasting flank-stripe; orange morph is pale rusty brown above and pinkish buff below. Upper lip has 8-9 well-defined wrinkles on each side and many spoon-hairs. Wings and uropatagium are dark brown. Ears are dark brown and relatively long (almost reaching muzzle when laid flat), inner margins connected by interaural band of skin having forward-facing fold. Tragus is minute, and concealed by antitragus, which is large and trapezoid. Anterior palate is closed, and basisphenoid pits are deep. As is typical for 
<taxonomicName box="[1461,1531,3429,3462]" class="Mammalia" family="Molossidae" genus="Mops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="656" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Mops</taxonomicName>
, cusps on M? have third ridge much reduced.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="657" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="38.[136,1343,279,746]" pageId="38" pageNumber="657">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[138,249,279,312]" pageId="38" pageNumber="657">Habitat.</emphasis>
[Lowland forest. Trevor's Free-tailed Bat may be a forest-savanna mosaic specialist. In 
<collectingCountry box="[274,379,319,352]" name="Nigeria" pageId="38" pageNumber="657">Nigeria</collectingCountry>
, the species has been observed flying over a fish pond close to tropical moist forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
